in uno Cornelio . . . Ovios . . . Fabios: enfranchised slaves generally adopted the praenomen and nomen qentilicium of their former masters. Thus the enfranchised slave of M. Tullius Cicero was M. Tullius Tiro. To the praenomen and nomen was added generally the name he had borne as a slave. The names in the text show that the members of Cornelian, Ovian, and Fabian qentes were concerned in bringing about the respective enfranchisements. Instead of Ovios and fabios, there is another reading, obvios and fabros.
